// help.grif - GRIF format
@abs(x)
	Returns the absolute value of 'x'.\n\nReturns an error if 'x' is not numeric.
@add(x,y)
	Returns the value of integer 'x' + integer 'y'.\n\nReturns an error if either are not numeric.
@addlist(key,x)
	Adds value 'x' to the end of list named 'key'.
@addto(key,x)
	Adds the integer value of 'x' to the value in 'key' and saves back to 'key'.\n\nReturns an error if either are not numeric.
@and
	In @if or @while, this separates multiple conditions.\n\nIf the previous condition is false, it short-circuits and returns false. It does not check the rest of the conditions but jumps to the next @elseif, @else, or @endif. Otherwise it continues on and checks the next condition.
@bitwiseand(x,y)
	Returns a bitwise AND of integer values 'x' and 'y'.\n\nFor example, @bitwiseand(7,2) = 2, since 7 = 111 binary and 2 = 010 binary and the result is 010 binary.\n\nReturns an error if either are not numeric or are less than zero.
@bitwiseor(x,y)
	Returns a bitwise OR of integer values 'x' and 'y'.\n\nFor example, @bitwiseor(7,2) = 7, since 7 = 111 binary and 2 = 010 binary and the result is 111 binary.\n\nReturns an error if either are not numeric or are less than zero.
@bitwisexor(x,y)
	Returns a bitwise XOR of integer values 'x' and 'y'.\n\nFor example, @bitwiseand(7,2) = 5, since 7 = 111 binary and 2 = 010 binary and the result is 101 binary.\n\nReturns an error if either are not numeric or are less than zero.
@cleararray(key)
	Clears all values from the array named 'key'.
@clearbit(x,b)
	Sets bit 'b' in integer value 'x' to 0, with b = 0 to 30. Lowest bit is on the right.\n\nReturns an error if either are not numeric, below zero, or 'b' is over 30.
@clearlist(key)
	Clears all values from list named 'key'.
@comment(value)
	Used for comments in scripts. This is completely ignored. Surround 'value' with quotes.\s
@concat(x,y,...)
	Concatenates the values supplied and returns the result.
@contains(x,y)
	Returns true/false if string 'x' contains string 'y'. Case is ignored.
@containslist(key1,key2)
	Returns true/false if list 'key1' contains all values in list 'key2'. Case is ignored.
@datetime(format)
	Returns the current local datetime using a valid .NET format pattern. Use quotes around the pattern. Timezone in returned in ExtraValue.\n\nFor example, @datetime("MM/dd/yyyy HH:mm") might return "01/17/2020 15:23", and the ExtraValue might be "-05:00" for US Eastern time zone.
@datetime(format,utc)
	Returns the current universal datetime using a valid .NET format pattern. Use quotes around the pattern. A timezone of "UTC" in returned in ExtraValue.\n\nFor example, @datetime("MM/dd/yyyy HH:mm") might return "01/17/2020 15:23". The ExtraValue will always be "UTC".
@debug(value)
	This command is enabled if the value in "system.debug" = "true". Otherwise it is ignored. It outputs the value plus a newline. Surround the value with quotes if it is a literal.
@div(x,y)
	Returns integer result of integer 'x' divided by integer 'y'.\n\nReturns an error if either are not numeric or 'y' equals zero.
@divto(key,x)
	Sets key to integer result of value in 'key' divided by 'x'.\n\nReturns an error if either are not numeric or 'x' equals zero.
@do
	In a @while loop, marks the end of conditions and starts the statement block.
@else
	If all conditions in @if and all @elseif are false, the statements in the @else block are run. @else is optional.
@elseif
	If all conditions in an @if are false, starts a new set of conditions. There can be multiple @elseif condition blocks. @elseif is optional.
@endfor
	End of a @for loop.
@endforeachkey
	End of a @foreachkey loop.
@endforeachlist
	End of a @foreachlist loop.
@endif
	End of an @if block.
@endwhile
	End of a @while loop.
@eq(x,y)
	Returns true/false if 'x' equals 'y'. Compares as numeric if possible. Otherwise it compares as strings ignoring case.
@exec(value)
	Executes the value as a script. Must surround the value with quotes to prevent it from being evaluated incorrectly.
@exists(key)
	Returns true/false if 'key' exists and value is not "null" or an empty string.
@false(x)
	Returns "true" if 'x' is falsey or "false" otherwise.\n\nFalsey values are "false", "f", "no", "n", "0", and "", ignoring case.\n\n"null" is neither truthy or falsey and will return "false". Any invalid value will return "false".\n\nThis is exactly the same as "@isfalse(x)".\n
@flipbit(x,b)
	Sets bit 'b' in 'x' to the opposite 0/1, with b = 0 to 30. Lowest bit is on the right.\n\nReturns an error if either are not numeric, below zero, or 'b' is over 30.
@for(x,start,end)
	Runs the @for loop, replacing "$x" inside with values from start to end inclusive as increasing integers.
@foreachkey(x,prefix,[suffix])
	Gets a list of keys with the specified prefix and optional suffix. Executes the @foreachkey loop, replacing "$x" with the part of the key after removing prefix and optional suffix.
@foreachlist(x,listname)
	Executes the @foreachlist loop. For each item in listname, replace "$x" with the value from the list.
@format(pattern,x0,x1,...)
	Replace the pattern values "{0}", "{1}", ... with the value x0, x1, ...
@frombinary(x)
	Converts the binary string x to an integer. @frombinary(11111111) = 255.
@fromhex(x)
	Converts the hex string x to an integer. @fromhex(FF) = 255.
